Pesha and Gusa (2013) indicate that people tolerate uncertainty in relationships within their cultures and they submit to marriage even when they are aware that they were going to be mistreated by a partner. This strengthens their relationships, which encourages the continuation of the cult while the choice of divorce remains a taboo. Despite this acceptance of personality, Nyawaga and Ololch (2017) note that people often get into marriages with the intention to be happy and this brings out the deliberateness to uphold marriage regardless of the challenges.
The Ugandan society is increasingly changing by borrowing western peoples’ cultures and ways of living like divorce. A study by Buss et al. (2011) attributes divorce to the changing ideologies in relationships. Ugandan marriages have changed from patriarchal contexts to less control by husbands since the western culture is dominant. The unwritten rules of marriage have changed through the creation of more liberal attitudes in marriage which create room for divorce.
Mittermaier (2011) explain divorce as a liberal response to different challenges in the marriage and points out that it is rare, but it happens for specific reasons. People do not decide to divorce after only a few months of union; it takes a couple of months and years for them to identify immaturity of the other partner in marriage and other areas which are not compatible with marriage.
